## Challenges Solved

In this sprint I had a hard time setting up my development, getting react working correctly and displaying.
I used Laravel Valet to host my website @ vite.portfolio.test. I figured out that to get react working for the 
front end of things I needed to use npm run dev. I had removed the bootstrap & react external dependencies via
<link> into internal ones with vite and npm to keep track of the versions. I learned alot about statemanagement
in react, how to run functions, pass parameters, and render dynamic UI elements. I was going to use traditional
api calls to send JSON data to the backend however after some research it seems like using RESTful Laravel routes
with web.php would be the most familiar and keeps everything in one file for simplicity. I started out by saving
the data to local storage via JSON. This worked and made things easy however I found that I could manipulate the 
cookies to cheat the game and the local storage wouldn't persist when closing. So I decided to use my api calls for
loading and saving json data via the ClickerHeroController in /Controllers/APi/. This way when the react app mounts
I can grab the data from the database and if it's not there initialize the records. Making the model and migrations
seemed pretty easy at this point so I was able to work fast. Though the only hard part I found with it was using a
foreign key of user_id from the users table. When placing the UI elements I reached for CSS to make a grid of 16 x 16
to place the items easily and rearrange them.Once I was able to save the JSON to the database after verifying the data
I began to make the auto save timer. Now that I had a timer for 30 seconds I decided to check if anything changed in the last
30 seconds before doing an api call with createOrUpdate() method and if it hadn't then it skipped the auto save reducing the amount of operations.
Also I saved on memory with the foreign key by forcing a unique record per user. However this does mean that there is 
only one save per user, I might change that down the line but for now this made sense. I made a double score button
that doubles the amount of score per click. I made the costs increase in a logarithmic format so that even though the
score goes up it still takes about the same amount of clicks to progress to the next one and it makes it easy to figure
out how many scores to add. This way later on I can get rid of the array and make it endless by doing math operations
to determine the cost and score per click! When deployed to prod I just needed to reduce the console.log info as to not
show the user what the saved data is. I still kept information to the user like, "save successful" to show viewers
that stuff is happening without giving away anything! Now I'm moving onto the next sprint!
